{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BZ8kkZQjFcN4Nbt1UmEkoF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"All commands require authentication. But the admin user doesn't exist. This seems contradictory. \n\nLet me think about this differently. Maybe:\n1. The MongoDB auth is enabled but the admin user was created with a different username\n2. Or there's another way to get the credentials\n\nLooking at the MongoDB auth flow with keyFile:\n- When using `--auth` with `--keyFile`, MongoDB requires authentication for ALL connections INCLUDING from localhost\n- The localhost exception is DISABLED when a keyFile is used (in MongoDB 3.6+)\n\nFrom MongoDB docs: \"When using x.509 authentication or other methods, the localhost exception is disabled.\"\n- With keyFile authentication, the localhost exception is typically disabled since it's meant for cluster-internal communication\n- The error message shows it's trying to authenticate as \"admin\" but that user doesn't exist in the admin database\n- This suggests the system is configured to require authentication, but there's no way to bootstrap the initial admin user\n\nLet me examine the StatefulSet configuration more closely to see if there's an initialization script or lifecycle hook that should have created the admin user during pod startup.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":716,"cache_read_input_tokens":37529,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":716},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ea574fa8-f5dc-4b1c-a27b-7e1c4157dac8","uuid":"f584155c-744e-486b-855a-f16108856c9a","request_id":"req_011CccMFKTKnVtHxYYL8keJE"}
